recordings.rmk:
Dark-eyed Junco x White-crowned Sparrow intergeneric hybrid (see photo by Ann Stockert on ebird: https://ebird.org/hotspot/L251839 ).   He (apparently only males sing the trill songs, both sexes sing the complex song) landed in a small bush (half meter) along the trail. He started singing about one minute after I started recording, 3 meters away, and stopped singing and flew away when someone walked past. There’s a long pause from six minutes to 9:41.0 (click to skip ahead).________

Hybrid’s regular trill: 0:13.0 , 0:36.6 , 1:00.9 . ________Hybrid’s regular trill with accent note at the end: 0:02.0 , 1:34.0 , 1:43.0 , 2:13.0 . ________ Hybrid’s two part trill: 3:38.0, 4:21.0 , 5:38.3 .________Dark-eyed Junco in background: 1:03.0 .  ________Oak Titmouse: 5:03.0 .  ________I am curious as to whether this hybrid sings just like a regular DEJU or not. I recorded a Dark-eyed Junco “seen” singing a “bell-like” trill unlike the hybrid’s trill (XC714337). ________An “unseen” bird was singing a two part trill that was almost identical to the hybrid’s, shortly after I recorded the hybrid (XC714338). If the unseen two part trill song was a DEJU’s, then the hybrid has learned this song well. But it could have been the hybrid singing. I hope to record some more DEJUs at this same location, to help answer this question.  (Addendum: I've decided the two-part trill referenced above is from the hybrid with 90% certainty. Here is a DEJU singing a different two-part trill along with the hybrid's regular trill: XC718210 ).__________Here's another song type recorded about two and a half weeks earlier, a seen DEJU: XC714315. ________ (Sennheiser ME62 omni mic, 24 inch Roché parabola, Marantz PMD 661. I edited this recording to lower the volume of the airplane flying over, but the hybrid sang only one trill song during this time).

recordings.loc: DeLaveaga Park (near  Santa Cruz), Santa Cruz County, California
recordings.rmk: This recording was not significantly modified, other than perhaps some removal of handling noise. Its focal bird is the one which trills twice, but other juncos can be heard calling and countersinging in the background. The bird was around or slightly above my head height (roughly 168 cm), on the fallen remains of a bishop pine, *Pinus muricata*. Surrounding vegetation includes rattlesnake grasses, Monterey pines, coyote brush, and coast live oak, among other plants. I'm not sure if I saw this bird or not, though I definitely saw quite a few juncos in the area of the pine and surrounding debris. When I made the recording, it was in fairly good lighting conditions, approaching sunset. The weather was clear. Though this bird was most likely of the local subspecies, *J. h. pinosus*, I'm not comfortable going any more specific than "Oregon subspecies group."

recordings.loc: Palace of Fine Arts (near  San Francisco), San Francisco County, California
recordings.rmk:
Three dependent juvenile plumaged Dark-eyed Junco (Oregon) were in area and were being fed by an adult Dark-eyed Junco (Oregon). If I recall they had nearly full-grown tails and were perhaps a week out of the nest. This recording was made at the Palace of Fine Arts, San Francisco, California (WGS84 37.802340, -122.448028). These birds were flitting around on the ground at my feet and were being fed by an adult. Two juvenile call types were recorded in this 134 second long recording: first was a buzzy begging note (quite variable) sometime given singly, other times repeated and when very excited (such as when adult approached with food) it was given rapidly. More rarely a second call was given—a brief chip—likely an analogue to the adult Chack note.  The adult Chack call was described in the BNA account as: Chack, also interpretable as tik, stip (Fig. 2F): wide-frequency, short-duration single syllable, often uttered near ground predator (Hostetter 1961); general alarm call during winter (Whitney 1968).

This recording was made with an iPhone 5s with the built-in microphone and the Røde Rec application. This recording has not been modified in any manner. This recording has some city type noises in the background.

Dark-eyed Junco (Oregon): 

begging: begins at 0:00  with an intense volley of begging is at 1:29
chipping: begins at 1:10 and at times blends into a begging note.

Song Sparrow (song): 0:00, 0:15, 0:31, 0:39

Allen’s Hummingbird: 0:15

European Starling: 0:53, 0:58, 0:59

White-crowned Sparrow (song): 1:04, 1:17

Mallard 1:36

recordings.loc: Oxford, Lafayette County, Mississippi
recordings.rmk:
Perched in the middle branches of 4m pine tree along the fenceline. Flushed from the adjacent grass into the tree and appeared to be agitated by my presence. Vocalized as it flew across my path within about 5m of the microphone.

#Editing#
Heavily edited to highlight the call notes. FFT filter in Adobe Audition, Blackman window, 2048 pts, 6kHz-14kHz. Then amplified 6dB.

#Habitat#
State waterfowl refuge along the margins of USACE flood control reservoir. Strip along the lake margins ~1km wide of moist soil grassland with mix of forbs, native warm season grasses (Andropogon, Schyzachyrium, Eragrostis, Aristida, etc.), and some sparse woody vegetation (Cephalanthus, Quercus saplings, etc.) bounded by oak hickory forest and, in places, pine plantation.  Three or four shallow waterfowl impoundments partially flooded in the winter.
